\begin_layout Abstract
The status motivation for consumption has generated an immense interest
 in the developed economies at a time when social mobility has been relatively
 stagnant.
 Considering the disparate environment of a developing economy where income
 inequalities are stronger and status rewards comprise of simple improvements
 in lifestyle and wealth - we view status games as those that generate positive
 externality instead of being wasteful.
 Viewing status consumption as a self-enhancement cost and status as expected
 economic rewards in the game where consumers transition through income
 bands, we comment on the effects of a rise in long-term income differences
 on status consumption.
\end_layout

