\begin_layout Standard
Given the positive externalites from the status games in the economy of
 income inequalities, status consumption is viewed as a direct investment
 for self-improvement for the consumer.
 This aims to represent the real-world conditions where the status competitions
 are ubiquitous through everyone’s participation (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,GoldmanPapsonSignWars1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) but are constrained by real wealth due to the high status being ultimately
 driven by economic gains and enjoyed by a small section of society.
 Since status is observed in the immediate context of the consumer, it is
 does not seem paradoxical that status games both limit the exclusive status
 to a small section while letting all sections participate (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RuncimanRelativeDeprivationSocialJustice1966"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a historical survey on reference groups).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The persistent inequalities in the economy grant the consumer in the model
 both a self-enhancement incentive (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "woodtaylorselfrelevantgoals1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and a mimetic tendency (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GarrelsMimesisAndScience2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) to emulate the rich.
 Status is viewed only as the expected accumulated wealth at a certain risk
 over the long term in a game where the consumer obtains a fixed disposable
 income by belonging to an income band (at a a given time).
 Thus while income is fixed for all consumers in the same band, the status
 competitions in every income band also provide a probabilistic transition
 to a richer income band - so that status consumption, as an investment
 for self-improvement, increases the probability of promotion (and the security
 against demotion) to a richer (poorer) band.
 The solution of the model uses the conditions of stability for a feasible
 growth of (risky) wealth under an observed probability of upwards or downwards
 transition.
\end_layout

