\begin_layout Standard
It is worth reiterating that the sense of status consumption as wasteful
 consumption in excess of needs is not relevant to the above self-enhancement
 notion of status consumption.
 If status games can be assumed to generate positive externalities, then
 the distinction between a necessity and excess is unimportant - if distinguisha
ble at all - for status consumption.
 Thus buying a luxury watch or joining a club membership is not meant to
 offer an income reward to consumer in the future (or that they are bought
 for such a purpose) - but the status benefit from having a luxury watch
 or a club membership carries a meaning to the consumer only if it is associated
 with real wealth (albeit at risk) in the long-term.
 The raison d’etre of status consumption is thus comprised within a certain
 mimetic association with the rich and the promotion (or demotion) to richer
 (poorer) bands - encapsulating processes that may be social (e.g.
 by allowing the consumer to engage with richer members in club who can
 more readily afford the status good) or emotional (by instilling self-confidenc
e or improving self-esteem) but relate to the long-term mobility that maintains
 income inequalities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above notion of status consumption evidently deviates from the futility
 view of conspicuous consumption (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals,HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - bearing more similarity with the rent-seeking approaches to status in
 the literature (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TullockEfficientRentSeeking2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 As we have argued, neither the status games nor the investments towards
 success in them are futile when the future wealth states of the consumer
 depend on the investments made by the consumer.
 The private pleasure which the overworked clerk receives in giving or receiving
 the most expensive gifts might classify as conspicuous consumption from
 a certain perspective - but the investment sense of status consumption
 under “productive” status competitions may treat gift-exchanges as relevant
 only as long as they are associated with higher-income groups and bring
 real gains to the consumer.
 The consumer utility is achieved not directly through the references either
 (as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004,OxobyCognitiveDissonanceStatus2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) but through states that are driven by the reference - a treatment that
 is similar to the approach followed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColeMaliathSocialNorms1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is worth emphasising that no variation in traits is assumed for the
 consumers (as is assumed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - since status is realised only through performance in the status competitions
 pertaining to each income-band.
