\begin_layout Standard
As consumers move up or down the hierarchy of income bands with a certain
 probability, the key condition for the long-term stability comes from the
 stability of sub-populations within these bands.
 The other important condition we utilise is that the status competitions
 must stay lucrative for participants in all income-bands in the long-term.
 Simply put, the latter condition implies that the rich consumer must not
 feel that there is too little price for which the poorer consumer is offered
 a chance to be rich while the poorer consumer must not feel that there
 is nothing on offer for mobility through status competitions to the richer
 position.
 In a simplified consideration of two income- bands, we discuss the implications
 of the above two conditions on the equilibrium and a feasible probability
 of transition.
 With status consumption as the cost of participation in status competitions,
 we then discuss how a consumer may balance accumulating wealth at risk
 while maintaining a fair chance to improve or maintain her social position.
\end_layout

