\begin_layout Standard
One of the implications of the two long-term equilibrium conditions - i.e.
 band population stability and appeal of status competitions across all
 bands - is that status consumption for the poorer consumer need not decline
 with narrowing of income differences.
 Equivalently, the costs to maintain the high wealth for the richer consumer
 may rise with narrowing of income differences in the long-term.
 As such, while wider income differences intensify status competitions and
 increase status consumption in the short-term, the long-term equilibrium
 conditions of population stability and universal appeal of status competitions
 imply a different dynamics so that the wider income differences act to
 reduce status consumption by making band-promotion more difficult (for
 the poor consumers) and band-security cheaper (for the richer consumers).
 Similarly, it is also ensured that a narrowing of income-differences in
 the long-term increases the value of (utility from) the status consumption
 for poorer consumers - so that the poorer consumers spend less on status
 investments while the richer consumers raise their status consumption to
 maintain their position of wealth.
\end_layout

